anced through rhetoric and metaphors, form, images, and symbols. To further develop this argument, the book is divided into chapters, each of which is based on a different musical form. Law, for Manderson, should strive for neither coherence nor integrity. Rather, it is imperfectly realized, constantly reinterpreted, and always in flux. Songs without Music is written in an original, engaging, and often humorous style, and exhibits a deep knowledge of both law and music. It successfully traverses several disciplines and builds an original and persuasive argument for a legal aesthetic. The book will appeal to a broad readership in law, political theory, literary criticism, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLaw and aesthetics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aargument.  aargumentation.  acomposition.  acreative nonfiction.  acultural studies.  aform.  ajustice.  alaw.  alegal argument.  alegal brief.  alegal interpretation.  alegal precedence.  alegal text.  alegal writing.  aliterary criticism.  aliving constitution.  aliving law.  ametaphor.  amusic theory.  amusic.  amusical forms.  anarrative structure.  anarrative theory.  anonfiction.  aphilosophy.  apolitical theory.  arhetoric.  asymbolism.  atext.  awriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021688440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092221140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922211423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520922211/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY